ions over retribution’s role in punishment reflect the shift in political philosophy from classical republicanism to modern notions of individual natural rights and the social contract.This book will be vital reading for political theorists, philosophers, criminologists, and legal scholars looking for a new perspective on the moral challenges faced by the modern criminal justice system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofxPhilosophy. 0aJustice pénalexAdministrationxPhilosophie. 0aPeinesxPhilosophie. 0aPunishmentxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPunishmentxPhilosophy. 0aPunishmentxPolitical aspects. 0aPunitionxAspect moral. 0aPunitionxAspect politique. 7aLAW / Administrative Law & Regulatory Practice.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266770940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442667709423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442667709.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles